\par "Did y'all find some help?" he asked without looking at me.
\par "Yes sir," I said proudly. "Mexicans and hill people."
\par "How many Mexicans?"
\par "Ten," I said, as if I'd personally rounded them up.
\par "That's good. Who are the hill people?"
\par "The Spruills. I forgot where they're from."
\par "How many?" He finished a stalk and crept forward, with his heavy sack inching along behind him.
\par "A whole truckload. It's hard to tell. Gran's mad because they've set up camp in the front yard, even got a fire goin' where home plate is. Pappy told 'em to set up by the silo. I heard him. I don't think they're real smart."
\par "Don't be sayin' that."
\par "Yes sir. Anyway, Gran's not too pleased."
\par "She'll be all right. We need the hill people."
\par "Yes sir. That's what Pappy said. But I hate they've messed up home plate."
\par "Pickin' is more important than baseball these days."
\par "I guess." Maybe in his opinion.
\par "How are the Mexicans?"
\par "Not too good. They stuffed 'em in a trailer again, and Mom's not too happy about it."
\par His hands stopped for a second as he considered another winter of squabbles. "They're just happy to be here," he said, his hands moving again.
\par I took a few steps toward the trailer in the distance, then turned to watch him again. "Tell that to Mom."
\par He gave me a look before saying, "Did Juan make it?"
\par "No sir."
\par "Sorry to hear that."
\par I'd talked about Juan for a year. He had promised me last fall that he'd be back. "That's okay," I said. "The new guy is Miguel. He's real nice."
