\par I thanked him and crept back to the house and onto the front porch without waking a single Spruill. I curled into the swing as if I'd been napping all along. No one was stirring, but I couldn't sleep. A breeze came from nowhere, and I daydream
ed of a lazy afternoon on the porch, no cotton to be picked, nothing to do but maybe fish in the St. Francis and catch pop flies in the front yard.
\par The work almost killed me during the afternoon. Late in the day, I limped toward the cotton trailer, lugging my harvest behind me, hot and thirsty, soaked with sweat, my fingers swollen from the tiny shal\-
low punctures inflicted by the burrs. I already had forty-one pounds for the day. My quota was still fifty, and I was certain I had at least ten pounds in my s
ack. I was hoping my mother would be somewhere near the scales because she would insist that I be allowed to quit and go to the house. Both Pappy and my father would send me back for more, quota or not.
\par Only those two were allowed to weigh the cotton, and if they hap\-pened to be deep in a row somewhere, then you got a break while they worked their way back to the trailer. I saw neither of them, and the idea of a nap flashed before me.
\par The Spruills had gathered at the east end of the trailer, in the shade. They were sitting on their bulky cotton sacks, resting and look\-ing at Trot, who, as far as I could tell, hadn't moved more than ten feet during the entire day.
\par I freed myself from the shoulder strap of my cotton sack and walked to the end of the trailer. "Howdy," one of the Spruills said.
\par "How's Trot?" I asked.
\par "Reckon he'll be all right," Mr. Spruill said. They were eating crackers and Vienna sausages, a favorite pick-me-up in the fields. Sit\-ting next to Trot was Tally, who completely ignored me.
\par "You got anything to eat, boy?" Hank suddenly demanded, his liquid eyes flashing at me. For a second I was too surprised to say any\-thing. Mrs. Spruill shook her head and studied the ground.
\par "Do you?" he demanded, shifting his weight so that he faced me squarely.
\par "Uh, no," I managed to say.
\par "You mean 'No sir,' don't you, boy?" he said angrily.
\par "Come on, Hank," Tally said. The rest of the family seemed to withdraw. All heads were lowered.
\par "No sir," I said.
\par "No sir what?" His voice was sharper. It was obvious Hank enjoyed picking fights. They'd probably been through this many times.
\par "No sir," I said again.
\par "You farm people are right uppity, you know that? You think you're better than us hill folk 'cause you have this land and 'cause you pay us to work it. Ain't that right, boy?"
\par "That's enough, Hank," Mr. Spruill said, but he lacked conviction. I suddenly hoped Pappy or my father would appear. I was ready for these people to leave our farm.
\par My throat constricted, and my lower lip began to shake. I was hurt and embarrassed and didn't know what to say.
