\par The other Siscos cowered behind one another while their three heroes floundered in the dirt.
\par The fight should've been over, but Hank had other plans. With de\-light and deliberation, he kicked each of the three in their faces and heads until they stopped moving and groaning. The crowd began to disperse.
\par "Let's go," a man said from behind me. "You kids don't need to see this." But I couldn't move.
\par Then Hank found a broken piece of an old two-by-four. For a mo\-ment the crowd stopped its exit to watch with morbid curiosity.
\par When Hank hit Jerry across the nose, someone in the crowd said, "Oh my God."
\par Another voice in the mob said something about finding the sheriff.
\par "Let's get outta here," an old farmer said, and the crowd began leaving again, this time a little quicker.
\par Hank still wasn't finished. His face was red with anger; his eyes flashed like a demon's. He kept pounding them until the old two-by-four began to shatter into small pieces.
\par I didn't see any of the other Spruills in the crowd. As the beating became a butchering, everyone fled. No one in Black Oak wanted to tangle with the Siscos. And now nobody wanted to face this madman from the hills.
\par When we were back on the sidewalk, those of us who'd seen the fight were silent. It was still happening. I wondered if Hank would beat them until they were dead.
\par Neither Dewayne nor I said a word as we darted through the crowd and ran toward the movie house.
