nd and screaming and begging to stop. A couple of years earlier in Monette, a chain had snapped, and a lit\-
tle girl had been flung across the midway and into the side of a trailer. The next week the Slinger was in Black Oak, with new chains, and folks lined up to ride it.
\par There were booths where you threw rings and darts and shot pel\-let pistols to win prizes. Some carnivals had fortune-tellers, others had photo booths, still others had magicians. They were all loud and colorful and filled with excitement. W
ord would spread quickly through the county, and people would flock in, and in a few hours Black Oak would be packed. I was desperate to go.
\par Perhaps, I thought, the excitement of the carnival would suppress any curiosity about Libby Latcher. I choked down my biscuits and ran outside.
