\par He tipped his hat to my mother and Gran and said, "Afternoon, Ruth, Kathleen."
\par "Hello, Stick," Gran said. "What can we do for you?"
\par "Lookin' for Eli or Jesse."
\par "They'll be along shortly. Somethin' the matter?"
\par Stick chewed on the blade of grass protruding from his lips and took a long look at the fields as if he were burdened with heavy news that might or might not be suitable for women.
\par "What is it, Stick?" Gran asked. With a boy off in the war, every visit by a man in a uniform was frightening. In 1944 one of Stick's predeces\-sors had delivered the news that my father had been wounded at Anzio.
\par Stick looked at the women and decided they could be trusted. He said, "That eldest Sisco boy, Grady, the one in prison for killin' a man over in Jonesboro, well, he escaped last week. They say he's back in these parts."
\par For a moment the women said nothing. Gran was relieved that the news wasn't about Ricky. My mother was bored with the whole Sisco mess.
\par "You'd better tell Eli," Gran said. "We need to fix supper."
\par They excused themselves and went into the house. Stick watched them, no doubt thinking about supper.
\par "Who'd he kill?" I asked Stick as soon as the women were inside.
\par "I don't know."
\par "How'd he kill him?"
\par "Beat 'im with a shovel's what I heard."
\par "Wow, must've been some fight."
\par "I guess."
\par "You think he's comin' after Hank?"
\par "Look, I'd better go see Eli. Where exactly is he?"
\par I pointed to a spot deep in the fields. The cotton trailer was barely visible.
\par "That's a far piece," Stick mumbled. "Reckon I can drive down there?" ;
\par "Sure," I said, already heading for the patrol car. We got in.
\par "Don't touch anything," Stick said when we were settled into the front seat. I gawked at the switches and radio, and of course Stick had to make the most of the moment. "This here's the radio," he said, pick\-
ing up the mike. "This here flips on the siren, this the lights." He grabbed a handle on the dash and said, "This here's the spotlight."
\par "Who do you talk to on the radio?" I asked.
\par "HQ mainly. That's headquarters."
\par "Where's headquarters?"
\par "Over in Jonesboro."
\par "Can you call 'em right now?"
