\par After supper I was watching my father patch an inner tube from our tractor when Tally appeared in the distance. It was late but not yet dark, and she seemed to cling to the long shadows as she moved t
oward the silo. I watched her carefully until she stopped and waved for me to follow. My father was mumbling, the patching was not go\-
ing well, and I slipped away toward the house. Then I ran behind our truck, found the shadows, and within seconds we were walking along a field row in the general direction of Siler's Creek.
\par "Where you goin'?" I finally asked, after it became apparent she was not going to speak first.
\par "I don't know. Just walkin'."
\par "You goin' to the creek?"
\par She laughed softly and said, "You'd like that, wouldn't you, Luke? You wanna see me again, don't you?"
\par My cheeks burned, and I couldn't think of anything to say.
\par "Maybe later," she said.
\par I wanted to ask her about Cowboy, but that subject seemed so ugly and private that I didn't have the nerv
e to go near it. And I wanted to ask her how she knew that Libby Latcher was telling that Ricky was the father of her baby, but again, it was something else I just couldn't bring up. Tally was always mysterious, always moody, and I adored her completely. 
Walking with her along the narrow path made me feel twenty years old.
\par "What did that deputy want?" she asked.
\par I told her everything. Stick had delivered no forbidden secrets. The Siscos were talking big, and they were crazy enough to try something. I relayed it all to Tally.
\par She thought about it as we walked, then asked, "Is Stick gonna ar\-rest Hank for killin' that boy?"
\par I had to be careful here. The Spruills were at war with each other, but any hint of an outside threat and they'd close ranks. "Pappy's worried about y'all leavin'," I said.
\par "What's that gotta do with Hank?"
\par "If he gets arrested, then y'all might leave."
\par "We ain't leavin', Luke. We need the money."
\par We had stopped walking. She was looking at me, and I was studying my bare feet. "I think Stick wants to wait till the cotton's in," I said.
