\par Late the next morning, with the sun trying its best to peek through the clouds, we returned to the fields to pick cotton. We were tired of sitting around the house watching the skies. Even I wanted to go to the fields.
\par The Mexicans were especially anxious to work. They were, after all, two thousand miles from home and not getting paid.
\par But the cotton was too wet and the ground was too soft. Mud caked on my boots, and it stuck to my picking sack, so that after an hour I felt as if I were dragging a tree trunk. We quit after two hours and left for the house, a sad and dispirited group.

\par The Spruills had had enough. It came as no surprise to see them breaking camp. They did so slowly, as if they were only reluctantly ad\-mitting defeat. Mr. Spruill 
