\par "Where's Eli?" she asked after we'd exchanged pleasantries.
\par "He stayed at home," I said, looking at the bin of Tootsie Rolls. She pointed and said, "Have one."
\par "Thanks. Where's Pop?"
\par "In the back. Just you and your parents, huh?"
\par "Yes ma'am. You seen 'em?"
\par "No, not yet. They buyin' groceries?"
\par "Yes ma'am. And I think my dad needs to borrow a phone." This stopped her cold as she thought of all the reasons why he needed to call someone. I unwrapped the Tootsie Roll.
\par "Who's he callin'?" she asked.
\par "Don't know." Pity the poor soul who borrowed Pearl's phone and wanted to keep the details private. She'd know more than the person on the other end.
\par "Y'all wet out there?"
\par "Yes ma'am. Pretty wet."
\par "That's such bad land anyway. Seems like y'all and the Latchers and the Jeters always get flooded first." Her voice trailed off as she contemplated our misfortune. She glanced out the window, slowly shaking her head at the prospect of another bleak harv
est.
\par I'd yet to see a flood\emdash at least not one that I could remember\emdash 
so I had nothing to say. The weather had dampened everyone's spirits, including Pearl's. With heavy clouds hanging over our part of the world, it was hard to be optimistic. Another gloomy winter was com\-ing.
\par "I hear some people are goin' up North," I said. I knew Pearl would have the details if the rumors were indeed true.
\par "I hear that, too," she said. "They're tryin' to line up jobs just in case the rains stay."
\par "Who's goin'?"
\par "Hadn't heard," she said, but I could tell from the tone of her voice that she had the latest gossip. The farmers had probably used her phone.
